open_data_statements: this questionnaire was a follow-up of the first trace survey which focused on non-bleeding critically ill patients.15 this study was endorsed by the european society of intensive care medicine (esicm) and by several national intensive care societies (data s2).;     the survey included a maximum of 50 questions divided into three subsections: respondents' demographics (7 questions) transfusion practice in the massively bleeding patient (7‚Äì 10 questions) and transfusion practices in the nonmassively bleeding patient (33 questions see data s1 for static version).;     f i g u r e 2 the use of tranexamic acid (txa) in massively (panel a) and non-massively (panel b) bleeding patients in the icu [color figure can be viewed at wileyonlinelibrary.com]  (table s1 in data s3).;     no consistent differences were observed between world regions (figures s2‚Äìs7 in data s1).;     whether the respondents would check the hb in between transfusions did not correlate with the transfusion thresholds in any of the subpopulations (figure s1 in data s4).;     no consistent differences were observed between world regions (figures s2‚Äìs7 in data s4).;     respondents who only sometimes or never checked the platelet count transfused at higher platelet counts in patients after cardiothoracic surgery (p = .044; figure s1 in data s4).;     anesthesiologists would transfuse at a higher hb level of 8 [7.4‚Äì9] g/dl versus internists 8 [7‚Äì9] g/dl (p = .044) (see table s2 in data s3).;     for platelet transfusion significant differences were observed in more patient categories (table s2 in data s3).;     a hospital-wide transfusion protocol did not affect the thresholds for rbc transfusion and fibrinogen administration (table s3 in data s3).;     the availability of an icu-specific transfusion protocol only showed an effect on the rbc transfusion threshold in ecmo patients (table s4 in data s3).

median across tissues of 15.0% range of 3.6‚Äì29.6% when excluding whole-blood data) and on average a 94.9% concordance in allelic directions (median 95.2%; range 86.7‚Äì99.2% when excluding whole-blood data) among the cis-eqtl for which the lead snp effect replicated in gtex data (supplementary note extended data fig. 1 and supplementary data 1).;     we focused on 10317 trait-associated snps (gwas p ‚â§ 5 √ó 10‚àí8; methods and supplementary table 3) and identified 59786 trans-eqtl (snp‚Äìgene distance >5 mb; p < 8.3 √ó 10‚àí6 corresponding to fdr < 0.05; supplementary data 2 and extended data fig. 2) representing 3853 snps (37% of tested gwas snps) and 6298 genes (32% of tested genes; fig. 1c).;     replication in purified cell types and cell lines identified 4018 (6.7%) trans-eqtl that replicated in at least one dataset or were supported by dna methylation quantitative trait locus (mqtl) data (benjamini‚Äìhochberg fdr < 0.05; 93.3% average allelic concordance; supplementary note supplementary fig. 5 and supplementary data 2).;     the replication rate in tissues from the gtex project23 was very low (discovery without gtex 0.07% of trans-eqtl replicated in any non-blood tissue 0.09% in blood benjamini‚Äìhochberg fdr < 0.05) but the allelic concordance of significant effects was on average 66% in non-blood tissues and 100% in blood (supplementary data 3).;     altogether 29207 (49%) of the reported trans-eqtl could be assigned a putative biological mechanism (fig. 3c and supplementary data 4).;     we identified 18210 eqtss (fdr < 0.05) representing 689 unique traits (55% of tested traits) and 2568 genes (13% of tested genes; supplementary data 5 and fig. 1d).;     ten eqtss replicated in lcl cells (benjamini‚Äìhochberg fdr < 0.05) and nine also had the same effect direction as that in the discovery dataset (supplementary fig. 12a and supplementary data 5) while 78 replicated in induced pluripotent stem cells (ipscs; benjamini‚Äìhochberg fdr < 0.05) with 71 (91%) showing the same direction (supplementary fig. 12b and supplementary data 5).;     we also identified 19 replicating eqtss (benjamini‚Äìhochberg fdr < 0.05 same effect direction) in the european subset of gtex samples (supplementary note and supplementary data 6) and observed an inflation of replication signal in some tissues primarily in blood (supplementary fig. 6b).;     most eqts associations (72.8%) represented blood cell traits (extended data fig. 3 and supplementary data 5).;     still in our blood data we also identified eqtss for non-blood pgss including metabolite and lipid levels anthropometric traits and diseases such as asthma celiac disease and coronary artery disease (supplementary note supplementary fig. 13a‚Äìc and supplementary data 5).
